e formation of a new industrial society of the second generation reliant on knowledge-intensive material production and gradual removal of humans from immediate material production processes. These two trends can fully develop only subject to the transition from the current socioeconomic formation to a non-economic one–the noonomy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industrial Management.2bisacsh  acivilizational crisis.  aeconomic history.  aindustrial society.  aindustry.  amodern technological shifts.  asocioeconomic.  atechnology.1 aDubrickson, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2z978311117804240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/979888719310640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9798887193106423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9798887193106/original  a978-3-11-102354-0  Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-117804-2  DG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2b2023  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles